# Tic-tac-toe write up attempt 1

## You will create tic tac toe NOW and learn how to code.

# The Board.

For tic tac toe you need a board, of course. [Arrays](https://www.w3schools.com/python/python\_arrays.asp). You should probably use them. You can also put arrays in arrays to make 2D arrays, and while not necessary it can be helpful and intuitive. You should probably have placeholder characters for spots that aren’t filled with x’s or o’s.

You will be needing this: [for loops](https://www.w3schools.com/python/python\_for\_loops.asp)

You also need to print the board, which is probably best done by shoving the board into a string which you can then print. You can loop over the array(s) and append each character to a string. To make new lines, use \\n (in a string). Please make this look good.  
![][/eames screenshots/Screenshot from 2024-08-29 13-21-08.png]  
Board, screenshots from Eames

# Getting user input

Now that you have a board and can print it, you need a way to have the user choose where they want to place their piece, which can be done with the [input() function](https://www.w3schools.com/python/ref\_func\_input.asp).   
![][image2]  
Getting input, changing character

# Changing the board

Now you have to turn their input into something you can use to replace a tile in your array. Helpful websites: [split()](https://www.w3schools.com/python/ref\_string\_split.asp), [int()](https://www.w3schools.com/python/ref\_func\_int.asp).  
You also must:

- Have some way of alternating between x’s and o’s  
- Make sure one player cannot write their piece another player’s piece (no playing in the same spots)  
- Make sure they cannot place piece out of the bounds of the board (optional, but suggested)

![][image3]  
Alternating

![][image4]

# Winning the game (or tying)

If you have done everything right, players can now place pieces on the board, but the game goes on forever. Someone needs to WIN. There are a couple ways to check for this, such as checking every possible combination, but that isn’t very fast. Perhaps you can group similar win conditions together and check for all of those at once. Also, make sure that the game ends when the board fills up even if no one won.
